"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Exodus chapters 22–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-exodus-22-24.py

Ch 22: Covenant code (Book of the Covenant continued) — theft, property damage,
       sexual ethics, religious apostasy (death penalty for sorcery and bestiality),
       treatment of the vulnerable (stranger/widow/orphan), lending/pledges, firstfruits.
Ch 23: Covenant code conclusion — honest judgment, Sabbath rest for the land,
       three annual festivals, the angel-guide, and the conquest promise.
Ch 24: Covenant ratification — Moses reads the Book of the Covenant, the blood
       of the covenant sprinkled, elders eat and drink before YHWH, Moses ascends
       for forty days to receive the tablets.

Key Christological frames for 22-24:
- The covenant-code laws as the moral architecture that Christ fulfills (Matt 5:17):
  not abolishing but fulfilling the ethical shape of the law.
- Lex talionis (22:23-24) as the measure of proportional justice Christ satisfies.
- The stranger/widow/orphan laws as the shape of Christ's own ministry (Luke 4:18).
- 'You shall be holy men to me' (22:31) as the OT counterpart of 'be holy as I am holy.'
- The angel guide (23:20-23) as the pre-incarnate Christ or divine messenger who
  carries YHWH's name.
- The three festivals as the liturgical calendar Christ fulfills:
  Passover/Unleavened Bread → crucifixion/burial; Firstfruits → resurrection;
  Weeks/Pentecost → Spirit-outpouring.
- The covenant blood of ch. 24 → Heb 9:18-21 citing Exod 24:8; 'This is the blood
  of the covenant' (Matt 26:28) is a direct quotation of 24:8.
- Moses's forty days on the mountain → Jesus's forty days in the wilderness.
- The elders eating and drinking before YHWH (24:9-11) → the Lord's Supper.
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>The law of theft: restitution in kind, with penalties scaled to the damage done and the stealth involved. The covenant law's restorative justice principle — paying back more than was taken — reflects the shape of Christ's atoning work: 'where sin increased, grace abounded all the more' (Rom 5:20). The thief must restore; Christ restored what he did not steal (Ps 69:4, applied typologically to his bearing of others' sin). Restitution defines the moral architecture that Christ's death satisfies.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Self-defense against a night-break-in with no guilt if the intruder dies — daylight brings liability. The distinction between night and day in assessing lethal defense reflects a moral principle about proportionality and certainty. The NT equivalent is Paul's distinction in Rom 13:12 between darkness and light as moral categories: 'the night is far gone; the day is at hand.' Moral clarity belongs to the daylight of the gospel; the ambiguities of pre-dawn judgment give way to the clear standards of the kingdom.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The thief must restore double what was stolen, selling himself into servitude if unable. The double-restitution principle embeds a surplus of justice: more is paid back than was taken. This is the shape of redemptive economics — Christ gives back more than Adam lost (Rom 5:15: 'the free gift is not like the trespass; for if many died through one man's trespass, much more have the grace of God and the free gift by the grace of that one man Jesus Christ abounded for many'). The law's restitution arithmetic points toward the overflowing grace of the gospel.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Restitution for stealing and keeping a living animal: double repayment for a donkey or sheep. The principle of living-thing restitution at double value introduces a proportionality in the law that will later be articulated as the mirror of justice. Christ's atonement satisfies proportional divine justice — not an approximate or discounted settlement but a full and adequate payment that meets the precise demand of the violated law.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A grazing animal eating another's field: the best of his own field/vineyard as restitution. The 'best of his own' standard requires not minimal compliance but sacrificial quality in making right what went wrong. The NT parallel is Paul's instruction on generosity: 'whoever sows sparingly will also reap sparingly' (2 Cor 9:6). The quality of restitution measures the seriousness of the covenant commitment — a pattern Christ fulfills by giving 'himself for us' as the best possible offering (Heb 7:27).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Fire spreading from one field to another — accidental but with full liability. The law does not distinguish sharply between intentional and negligent damage in property cases: the harm done creates the obligation, not only the intent. This strict liability principle points toward the comprehensiveness of Christ's bearing of sin's consequences — he bore not only the intentional sins but the full weight of human failure in all its dimensions (Isa 53:6: 'the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all').</p>",
    "7": "<p>Property placed in trust and stolen: full restitution if the thief is found; divine arbitration if not. The trust-and-betrayal scenario introduces the covenantal dimension of property law — the neighbor is held to the same standard of fidelity as a formal covenant partner. The NT develops the trust-theme in the parable of the talents (Matt 25:14–30): the master's property entrusted to servants, with strict accountability for its management. Stewardship is covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>When ownership is disputed and the thief not found, both parties come before YHWH (i.e., the judges) and the one found guilty pays double. The judicial process as access to divine adjudication: YHWH is the ultimate judge behind the human court. Jesus claims the same ultimate judicial authority: 'The Father judges no one, but has given all judgment to the Son' (John 5:22). Every human court is a derivative of the divine court to which all disputes ultimately come.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Disputes about lost property — ox, donkey, sheep, clothing — all come before the divine adjudicators. The comprehensive list of dispute types ensures no property category escapes the covenant's justice framework. The covenant code is not a selective law for major matters but a total ordering of human community life. Jesus similarly makes total claims on all of life: 'You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind' (Matt 22:37) — the covenant's total scope is intensified, not reduced.</p>",
    "10": "<p>An animal in trust that dies or is injured without anyone seeing: an oath before YHWH settles the matter. The oath-before-YHWH mechanism for unwitnessed events reflects the covenant's understanding that YHWH is always the witness: 'all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account' (Heb 4:13). Human witnesses can be absent; YHWH's presence is not. The oath system embeds the knowledge of divine omniscience into the legal order.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The oath accepted and no restitution required — but if the animal was stolen, restitution is owed. The oath-mechanism's integrity depends entirely on the reality of divine witness. The NT raises the stakes: Jesus teaches 'let what you say be simply Yes or No; anything more than this comes from evil' (Matt 5:37). The oath was the legal mechanism for invoking divine witness; Jesus calls his disciples to a level of integrity that makes the oath mechanism unnecessary.</p>",
    "12": "<p>If the animal in trust was seized (<i>ganav</i> by predators) and can be shown, no restitution. If killed by a wild animal and its remains brought as evidence, no restitution. The evidential principle — showing what remains — grounds legal decisions in verifiable reality. The NT's faith is similarly evidential: Christ's resurrection is the material evidence on which the gospel rests (1 Cor 15:14–15: 'if Christ has not been raised, your faith is futile'); the covenant law's demand for evidence of the claim mirrors the gospel's grounding in historical fact.</p>",
    "13": "<p>If someone borrows an animal and it is injured or dies in the owner's absence, full restitution. The borrower bears the full risk of the borrowed animal. The NT parallel is stewardship: 'it is required of stewards that they be found trustworthy' (1 Cor 4:2). What is borrowed — life, gifts, time, resources — is held under divine ownership and must be accounted for. Christ is the perfectly faithful steward who returned everything the Father gave him fully accounted (John 17:4).</p>",
    "14": "<p>If the owner is present when the animal is injured, no restitution — the owner's presence transfers the risk. The owner-present principle establishes that the owner's engagement with his property changes the liability. This maps onto the divine presence principle: when YHWH is present, the people are under his care and responsibility transfers to a different dynamic. Christ's incarnation is the supreme instance — the owner himself is present, bearing the full weight of what happens to his creation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>If someone seduces an unbetrothed virgin: he must pay the bride price and marry her; if her father refuses, he still pays the full bride price. The law treats the violated woman's honor as a property matter — a reflection of the law's ancient social context — but its enduring principle is that sexual exploitation creates obligation: the one who takes something that isn't his must pay fully. Christ's treatment of the marginalized and violated (Luke 7:36–50; John 8:1–11) consistently dignifies those the religious system had dismissed.</p>",
    "16": "<p>If her father refuses the marriage, the full bride-price equivalent is still paid. The financial obligation stands independent of the social outcome — the law creates accountability even when the relational damage cannot be fully repaired. The covenant logic: what has been wronged must be addressed, even if it cannot be fully undone. This is the structure of atonement — the debt acknowledged, paid, and absorbed even when the harm done cannot simply be reversed.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'You shall not allow a sorceress to live' — the death penalty for occult practice. Alongside idolatry and covenant-breaking, sorcery/witchcraft is a capital offense in the covenant code because it claims access to power outside YHWH's covenant framework: it is a practical denial of YHWH's sovereignty. The NT does not carry the judicial penalty into the new covenant community but maintains the spiritual seriousness: sorcery (<i>pharmakeia</i>) appears in Paul's lists of 'works of the flesh' (Gal 5:20) and among those excluded from the new Jerusalem (Rev 22:15).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Whoever lies with an animal shall be put to death.' The death penalty for bestiality marks the absolute categorical boundary between human and animal — the image-of-God status of the human person sets an inviolable boundary. The NT equivalent is the body-theology of 1 Cor 6:15–20: the body of the believer is a 'temple of the Holy Spirit' and cannot be used in ways that violate its nature. The covenant law's boundaries on bodily ethics are intensified, not abolished, in the new covenant.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Whoever sacrifices to any god other than YHWH shall be devoted to destruction.' The first-commandment seriousness: YHWH's exclusive covenant claim is enforced by the most severe penalty in the judicial code. The NT does not carry the judicial penalty but maintains the spiritual absolute: 'No one can serve two masters' (Matt 6:24); 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers' (2 Cor 6:14). The exclusive claim of YHWH on Israel becomes the exclusive claim of Christ on his people — a claim that tolerates no rival at the center.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'You shall not wrong a stranger or oppress him, for you were strangers in the land of Egypt.' The stranger-protection law grounds Israel's ethics in their own history of vulnerability: covenant ethics are motivated by memory. Jesus expands this to the comprehensive love of neighbor (Luke 10:29–37) and fulfills it in his own person — 'the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head' (Luke 9:58). The Lord of the covenant became himself the stranger, so that those who welcome the stranger welcome him (Matt 25:35).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The widow and orphan are placed under special divine protection — the three-fold marginalized category (stranger, widow, orphan) that runs through the prophets and NT. 'Religion that is pure and undefiled before God the Father is this: to visit orphans and widows in their affliction, and to keep oneself unstained from the world' (Jas 1:27). Jesus's ministry was concentrated among these groups — the marginalized found in him the advocate the covenant had promised them.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'If you afflict them, and they cry out to me, I will surely hear their cry.' YHWH as the direct advocate for those who have no human advocate. The divine responsiveness to the cry of the vulnerable is a covenant commitment: 'he will fulfill the desire of those who fear him; he also will hear their cry and save them' (Ps 145:19). Jesus identifies himself as the one who hears and answers the cry of those who call on him — 'everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved' (Rom 10:13).</p>",
    "23": "<p>If YHWH's anger burns against the oppressor of widows and orphans, their wives will become widows and their children orphans — the covenant consequence mirrors the covenant crime. This lex talionis principle in social justice matters is the structure of divine judgment: what you do to others returns to you (Matt 7:2: 'the measure you use will be measured back to you'). Christ bears this structure entirely on behalf of sinners — the judgment that should return to us fell on him.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Lending to the poor: no interest on loans to the poor among Israel's own people. The no-interest loan to the poor is a covenant act of solidarity — treating the poor person's crisis as a shared community problem rather than an investment opportunity. The NT's theology of generosity follows the same logic: 'lend, expecting nothing in return, and your reward will be great' (Luke 6:35). The covenant code's economic ethics anticipate the kingdom's inversion of normal economic logic.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The pledge: if a cloak is taken as security, it must be returned by nightfall — it is the poor person's only covering. The returning-the-cloak law treats the poor person's dignity and physical need as taking precedence over the creditor's legal rights. Jesus radicalizes this: 'if anyone would take your tunic, let him have your cloak as well' (Matt 5:40). The covenant code's cloak law and Jesus's cloak-teaching are both about radical prioritization of the other person's basic humanity over one's own legal claims.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'If he cries to me, I will hear, for I am compassionate (<i>chanun ani</i>).' The divine compassion is the covenant ground for the social-justice laws: YHWH is compassionate, so his covenant community must be compassionate. The character of YHWH determines the ethics of Israel. The same logic structures the NT ethics: 'Be merciful, even as your Father is merciful' (Luke 6:36); 'be kind to one another, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, as God in Christ forgave you' (Eph 4:32). Divine character is the ground and model of human conduct.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'You shall not revile God or curse a ruler of your people.' The prohibition against blasphemy and against cursing legitimate authority — both protected by the covenant code. The NT nuances: 'Honor everyone. Love the brotherhood. Fear God. Honor the emperor' (1 Pet 2:17). Paul cites the ruler-curse prohibition when accidentally addressing the high priest disrespectfully (Acts 23:5). The covenant code's protection of legitimate authority becomes the NT's theology of ordered society under God.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Firstfruits of harvest and firstborn of sons dedicated to YHWH — the redemption theme embedded in the law. The firstborn-to-YHWH principle was established in the Passover (Exod 13:2) and developed in the law. The NT picks up this language for Christ: 'the firstborn of all creation' (Col 1:15), 'the firstborn from the dead' (Col 1:18), 'the firstborn among many brothers' (Rom 8:29). Christ is the true firstfruits offering — the one dedicated entirely to YHWH who by his dedication makes all others acceptable.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The firstborn son is to be given to YHWH on the eighth day. The eighth day dedication: circumcision occurred on the eighth day (Lev 12:3), Jesus was circumcised on the eighth day (Luke 2:21). The eighth day in Hebrew thought transcends the seven-day week and points toward new creation — the day beyond the Sabbath, the day of resurrection. Jesus's resurrection is on the first day of the week, but this first day is simultaneously the eighth — the day of new creation that the firstborn-on-eighth-day dedication prefigured.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'You shall be holy men to me (<i>anshei qodesh*</i>).' The chapter's closing instruction: the covenant community is a holy community. The holiness demand recurs throughout Leviticus (11:44–45; 19:2; 20:26) and is explicitly taken up in the NT: 'as he who called you is holy, you also be holy in all your conduct, since it is written: You shall be holy, for I am holy' (1 Pet 1:15–16). Christ is himself the ground of the community's holiness — 'by God's doing you are in Christ Jesus, who became for us wisdom from God, righteousness, sanctification, and redemption' (1 Cor 1:30).</p>",
    "31": "<p>The torn-meat prohibition: do not eat meat torn by wild animals — give it to the dogs. The holiness principle extends to food — what Israel eats reflects who Israel is. The distinction between clean and unclean food is the bodily enactment of the covenant distinction between holy and common. Peter's vision (Acts 10:9–16) declares all foods clean — but this declaration is simultaneously the declaration that all peoples (not only Israel) are acceptable to YHWH. The food laws' Christological fulfillment is missiological: the abolition of food distinctions opens the table to the nations (Acts 10:28).</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>The judicial ethics begin: 'Do not spread a false report; do not join hands with a wicked man to be a malicious witness.' The covenant's justice system depends on the integrity of testimony — false witness destroys the entire judicial apparatus. The ninth commandment (against false witness) is the foundation; this verse applies it to the courtroom. Jesus faced false witnesses at his trial (Matt 26:59–61) — his condemnation was the covenant code's own violation turned against the covenant's author. The irony of the trial is that the one who legislated against false witness died by it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Do not follow the many to do evil, nor in a lawsuit side with the many to pervert justice.' The counter-cultural demand: popular consensus is not the standard of truth or justice. The law explicitly warns against majority pressure as a corrupting force. Jesus was condemned by popular demand ('crucify him!' Matt 27:23) — the crowd overwhelming Pilate's weak judgment is precisely the dynamic the law warned against. The NT call to 'not be conformed to this world' (Rom 12:2) continues the covenant code's resistance to crowd-ethics.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'And you shall not be partial to a poor man in his lawsuit.' The impartiality demand cuts both ways — not only in favor of the powerful but against the powerful and against romanticizing the poor. Justice is blind in both directions. The NT: 'You shall not be partial in judgment' (Deut 1:17) is taken up in Jas 2:1–9 as the prohibition against favoring the wealthy in the church assembly. God himself 'shows no partiality' (Acts 10:34; Rom 2:11).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Helping your enemy's ox or donkey back to him — the ethical demand that cuts across personal enmity. The obligation to help one's enemy's animal expresses the covenant principle that the law governs conduct independent of personal feeling. Jesus radicalizes: 'Love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you' (Matt 5:44). The enemy-animal law is the OT foundation for enemy-love — practical assistance to the one who opposes you before the full articulation of enemy-love as a positive command.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Helping an enemy's donkey lying under its load rather than leaving it. The animal-burden law again prevents personal enmity from overriding the moral duty to relieve suffering. The neighbor-obligation transcends the friend-limit. Christ fulfilled this by helping humanity even while 'we were enemies' (Rom 5:10) — bearing the weight of human sin was the ultimate relieving of the burden humanity had loaded onto itself and could not carry.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'You shall not pervert the justice due to your poor in his lawsuit.' After protecting against favoritism of the poor (v. 3), now protecting the poor from being stripped of justice. The law holds both poles: no special treatment in either direction, but active protection of those whose vulnerability makes them susceptible to being crushed by the judicial system. Jesus warns against the religious leaders who 'devour widows' houses' (Mark 12:40) — covenant-code violations in priestly dress.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Keep far from a false charge, and do not kill the innocent and righteous, for I will not acquit the wicked.' The absolute prohibition against condemning the innocent is the most solemn judicial command in the covenant code. The NT fulfills it by inversion: the innocent Jesus was condemned so that the guilty (us) might be acquitted. 'He made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God' (2 Cor 5:21). The law's prohibition against killing the innocent is violated at the cross — and that violation becomes the ground of salvation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'You shall take no bribe, for a bribe blinds the clear-sighted and subverts the cause of those who are in the right.' The bribe as the structural enemy of justice — it corrupts the judicial faculty itself ('blinds the clear-sighted'). Judas's thirty pieces of silver is the paradigmatic covenant-code bribe: the one who betrayed the righteous one for money (Matt 26:15) fulfilled the law's warning about what bribery does to justice. The high priest's payment of Judas was itself a bribed subversion of justice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'You shall not oppress a sojourner — you know the heart of a sojourner, for you were sojourners in the land of Egypt.' The empathy-grounded ethics recurs. The covenant code repeatedly returns to the exodus experience as the moral foundation for treatment of the vulnerable: you know what it is to be without rights, without protection, without home. The incarnation follows the same logic: Christ became a sojourner (John 1:14 — 'he tabernacled among us'; Luke 9:58 — 'no place to lay his head') so that he knows the heart of the stranger from the inside.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Sabbath year: six years sow and reap, the seventh year leave the land fallow for the poor and the wild animals. The sabbatical-year legislation extends the Sabbath principle from time to land — the land itself participates in YHWH's rest. The NT develops the Sabbath rest as eschatological: 'a Sabbath rest remains for the people of God' (Heb 4:9). The land's rest is a type of the final rest Christ secures — where the creation itself participates in the redemption (Rom 8:21).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The seventh year: whatever grows on its own is for the poor and the animals. The land's fallow produces food for those who have no fields. The Sabbath year is a built-in redistribution mechanism — the law arranges that the seventh year's spontaneous growth serves those who cannot afford to farm. The NT's generosity theology: 'At the present time your abundance may supply their want, so that their abundance may supply your want' (2 Cor 8:14). The covenant's economic Sabbath reflects the gospel's logic of sharing.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The weekly Sabbath restated — for the ox, donkey, servants, and sojourners to rest. The Sabbath's scope extends to every living being in Israel's household: no one and no animal within the covenant community's sphere is excluded from rest. Jesus declares 'the Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath' (Mark 2:27) — he restores the Sabbath to its creational purpose (rest for all) from its deformation as a burden-system. The breadth of the covenant Sabbath grounds Jesus's healings on the Sabbath as fulfillments of the law's deepest intent.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Pay attention to all that I have said to you, and make no mention of the names of other gods; let it not be heard on your lips.' The covenantal exclusivity is comprehensive: not only must Israel not worship other gods, they must not even mention them. The complete erasure of alternative divine names from Israel's speech is the verbal counterpart of the commandment against idolatry. The NT equivalent: 'But sexual immorality and all impurity or covetousness must not even be named among you' (Eph 5:3) — holiness excludes the very naming of what is incompatible with it.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Three times a year a festival to YHWH — the three annual pilgrimage feasts (Unleavened Bread, Weeks/Harvest, Ingathering/Booths) are the liturgical skeleton of Israel's year. These three become the template for NT fulfillment: Passover/Unleavened Bread → cross/burial; Firstfruits → resurrection; Weeks/Pentecost → the Spirit outpouring (Acts 2:1). The agricultural calendar of Israel's three feasts is fulfilled in the three watershed events of Christ's redemptive work in a single year.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Feast of Unleavened Bread: seven days, no leaven, in the month of Abib (the exodus month). 'No one shall appear before me empty-handed.' The feast commemorates the hasty exodus departure when there was no time for bread to rise. Paul uses the leaven-and-unleavened-bread imagery for the church: 'Christ our Passover has been sacrificed; therefore let us celebrate the festival, not with the old leaven, the leaven of malice and evil, but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth' (1 Cor 5:7–8). The feast's theological grammar becomes the NT's ethics of new-life consistency.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Feast of Harvest (Weeks/Shavuot/Pentecost): firstfruits of your labor. The Feast of Weeks fell fifty days after Passover — on which day the Holy Spirit was poured out in Acts 2. The Spirit's arrival on Pentecost is YHWH fulfilling the feast-calendar from within: the Feast of Harvest firstfruits becomes the firstfruits of the Spirit (Rom 8:23: 'we ourselves, who have the firstfruits of the Spirit'). The Spirit-gift is framed as the divine harvest's first yield.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Feast of Ingathering (Booths/Sukkot): at the end of the year when you gather in from the field. All three feasts require male attendance at the sanctuary. The Feast of Booths was associated with dwelling in temporary shelters commemorating the wilderness sojourn; John 7:37–39 — Jesus's great proclamation ('let anyone who thirsts come to me') — is delivered at the climax of the Feast of Booths. Jesus speaks of the Spirit as the fulfillment of the feast's central water-pouring ceremony.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'You shall not offer the blood of my sacrifice with anything leavened.' The Passover sacrifice and leavened bread are incompatible — the unleavened purity of the feast must be maintained at the moment of sacrifice. The NT application: the cross is performed in the context of Passover, not festival-leaven; the sacrifice that satisfies sin cannot coexist with the old leaven of sin. The ritual incompatibility is the theological principle: Christ's atoning work requires the complete removal of what it removes (1 Cor 5:7).</p>",
    "19": "<p>'The best of the firstfruits of your ground you shall bring into the house of YHWH your God.' The firstfruits principle: YHWH receives the first and best of every harvest — not the surplus after Israel's needs are met. The NT applies this to giving: 'Honor the LORD with your wealth and with the firstfruits of all your produce' (Prov 3:9, cited in 2 Cor 9:7–8). Christ is himself YHWH's firstfruits — the best given freely before anything else (1 Cor 15:23). The pattern of giving the firstfruits to God runs from creation-law through cross to new creation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'I am sending an angel before you to guard you on the way and to bring you to the place I have prepared.' The angel-guide is YHWH's personal mediatorial presence — this messenger 'carries my name' (v. 21), meaning he has YHWH's full authority and presence. This angel is identified in many traditions as the pre-incarnate Christ — the Angel of YHWH who functions as YHWH's personal presence in the OT. John 14:3 ('I go to prepare a place for you') echoes the angel-guide's function: Jesus himself is now the one who goes before to prepare the place of rest.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Pay careful attention to him and obey his voice; do not rebel against him, for he will not pardon your transgression, for my name is in him.' The angel's authority is YHWH's own — 'my name is in him' means he is the authorized bearer of the divine presence and character. This is the language of divine identity. John's Gospel uses the same identity-language for Jesus: 'I have come in my Father's name' (John 5:43); 'Holy Father, keep them in your name, which you have given me' (John 17:11). The Son bears the Father's name — the covenant-angel's identity-language is fulfilled in the incarnation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>If Israel obeys the angel, YHWH will be an enemy to their enemies and an adversary to their adversaries. The covenant protection is tied to the mediator's instructions — obedience to the angel-guide brings divine backing in every conflict. The NT equivalent: 'If God is for us, who can be against us?' (Rom 8:31). But this protection is accessed through the mediator — 'through our Lord Jesus Christ' (Rom 5:1). The angel-guide's protective function, accessed through obedience, becomes in Christ the full covenant protection accessed through faith.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The angel will bring Israel to the Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hivites, and Jebusites — the list of nations to be displaced. The land conquest is mediated through the angel. The NT recontextualizes: the greater conquest is not of ethnic nations but of principalities and powers (Eph 6:12). Christ led 'captivity captive' (Eph 4:8, citing Ps 68:18) — the triumphant procession of the new covenant's conquest of spiritual enemies, mediated through the one who carries the divine name.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'You shall not bow down to their gods or serve them or do according to their practices, but you shall utterly overthrow them and break their pillars in pieces.' The covenant exclusivity demands the dismantling of the competing religious systems — not coexistence but complete displacement. The NT does not call for physical destruction of pagan shrines, but maintains the spiritual absolute: 'what fellowship has light with darkness? What accord has Christ with Belial?' (2 Cor 6:14–15). Paul's ministry at Ephesus resulted in the burning of magical books and economic disruption of the idol trade (Acts 19:19–27).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'You shall serve YHWH your God, and he will bless your bread and your water, and I will take sickness away from among you.' The covenant blessing for obedience: provision and health from the hand of YHWH. The NT develops this blessing in terms of spiritual provision but also anticipates total physical restoration: 'He himself bore our sins in his body on the tree, that we might die to sin and live to righteousness. By his wounds you have been healed' (1 Pet 2:24). The covenant health promise reaches its ultimate fulfillment in the new creation where 'there will be no more death or mourning or crying or pain' (Rev 21:4).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'None shall miscarry or be barren in your land; I will fulfill the number of your days.' The fertility and longevity blessings extend the covenant's reach to the most intimate biological domains. These blessings were conditional on covenant faithfulness; the NT transforms the scope: the ultimate fulfillment is not long physical life but resurrection life — 'whoever believes in me, though he die, yet shall he live' (John 11:25). The full number of days promised in the covenant finds its ultimate answer in eternal life.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'I will send my terror (<i>emati</i>) before you and will throw into confusion all the people against whom you come.' The divine 'terror before' is the covenant's conquering force — YHWH goes ahead of Israel in battle. This is the pattern of the ark's presence (Joshua 3–6: the ark before Israel causes the Jordan to stop and Jericho's walls to fall). Jesus applies this to his ministry: 'I saw Satan fall like lightning from heaven' (Luke 10:18) — the advance of the kingdom carries the divine terror before it, defeating the powers.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'I will send hornets before you which shall drive out the Hivites, Canaanites, and Hittites from before you.' The hornets as YHWH's advance force — panic and natural disruption preceding the human army. The covenant promise is that YHWH fights on multiple fronts simultaneously: visible human warfare and invisible divine disruption. The NT's spiritual warfare has the same multi-front character: the Spirit's work goes ahead of the proclamation (Acts 16:14 — Lydia's heart 'the Lord opened'), preparing what human proclamation will then harvest.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'I will not drive them out from before you in one year, lest the land become desolate and the wild beasts multiply against you.' The deliberate gradualism of the conquest is divinely intended — not because YHWH lacks power but because the land requires the population to manage it. Divine purposes are frequently graduated: the kingdom comes like a mustard seed (Matt 13:31–32), not in a single overwhelming intervention but in patient, sustained growth until the full harvest. The gradualism is not weakness but wisdom.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Little by little I will drive them out from before you, until you have increased and possess the land.' The 'little by little' principle of the covenant is the OT form of what Jesus teaches as the kingdom's growth pattern (Matt 13:31–33). Both the Sinai covenant and the new covenant work on the same temporal logic: the promised inheritance is given in full at the legal/covenant level but possessed progressively in the experiential/historical level. Israel is already given the land; they must still take it. Believers already have every spiritual blessing (Eph 1:3); they must still live it out.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The covenant boundaries of the land: from the Red Sea to the Sea of the Philistines, from the wilderness to the Euphrates. The full extent of the promised land was never fully occupied even under David and Solomon. The NT reframes the promise: 'the meek shall inherit the earth' (Matt 5:5, citing Ps 37:11) — the land promise expands to creation-scope in the new covenant. What was given to Israel as a type (the land) is fulfilled in Christ as anti-type (the new creation, the whole earth).</p>",
    "32": "<p>'You shall make no covenant with them or with their gods.' The covenant-exclusivity principle in its social form: Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH cannot coexist with formal alliances with the nations in their gods' names. The NT equivalent: 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers' (2 Cor 6:14) — not a prohibition of all social contact but of the formal covenant-sharing (partnership, marriage, common worship) that would compromise the exclusive covenant bond with YHWH through Christ.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'They shall not dwell in your land, lest they make you sin against me; for if you serve their gods, it will surely be a snare to you.' The final warning of the covenant code: the moral threat of the nations in the land is their gods. The NT recognizes the same dynamic: 'bad company corrupts good morals' (1 Cor 15:33). The protective principle of the covenant — keeping the community distinct from what would corrupt the covenant bond — becomes the NT's call to holiness: 'come out from among them and be separate' (2 Cor 6:17, citing Isa 52:11).</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH tells Moses to come up with Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and seventy elders to worship at a distance. The covenant ratification ceremony requires representative witnesses — not all Israel (impossible) but its leadership in ascending tiers: the seventy elders (all Israel's representatives), Aaron and his sons (the priesthood), and Moses (the mediator). The hierarchical structure of the covenant community in its representative leadership anticipates the church's structure: elders, ministers, apostles — all ascending tiers of covenant accountability before God.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Moses alone shall come near to YHWH; the others shall not come near, and the people shall not come up with him.' The solitary mediator at the summit: Moses alone enters the divine presence at the top. The covenant structure is one of graduated nearness with the mediator at the pinnacle. The NT's counter-movement is striking: Christ is the mediator who has opened the way for all — 'let us draw near with a true heart in full assurance of faith' (Heb 10:22). What Moses alone could do, all believers now do through the one greater mediator.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Moses came and told the people all the words of YHWH and all the rules. The people's response: 'All the words that YHWH has spoken we will do.' The voice of the covenant community ratifying the covenant terms. This is the covenant oath of Exod 19:8 repeated with the full covenant code now articulated. The repetition marks the covenant commitment as deliberate and informed — they heard it all and said yes to it all. The NT equivalent is baptismal confession — a public, informed commitment to the covenant terms of the gospel.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moses wrote down all the words of YHWH, rose early, and built an altar with twelve pillars for twelve tribes. The written word as the covenant document and the twelve-tribe altar as the covenant community's representative structure. Writing gives the covenant permanence — it can be read, reviewed, challenged against its original text. The NT covenant document (the NT canon) serves the same function: the written witness to the covenant terms ratified at the cross, accountable to its text.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Young men of Israel offered burnt offerings and sacrificed peace offerings to YHWH. The young men (not yet the designated Levites — the Levitical priesthood is not yet established) perform the sacrifice at the covenant ratification. This unusual priestly action by non-designated young men at the covenant founding moment points toward the NT's 'priesthood of all believers' (1 Pet 2:9) — the covenant people as a whole are a 'royal priesthood,' not only the designated few.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses took half the blood and put it in basins; half he threw against the altar. The blood is divided: half to the altar (YHWH's side) and half to be thrown on the people (v. 8). The division of the covenant blood between YHWH's altar and the people is the OT's most explicit enactment of the covenant as a bond established in blood — the same blood touching both parties creates the bond between them. The Eucharist's two-party sharing (Christ's body and blood given to the community) is the NT fulfillment of this two-party blood application.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Moses took the Book of the Covenant and read it in the hearing of the people, who again said: 'All that YHWH has spoken we will do and we will be obedient.' The covenant document read publicly before the community commits — covenant ratification requires informed public consent. The reading of the covenant aloud to the assembled community becomes a recurring covenant-renewal pattern (Joshua 8:34–35; Neh 8:1–8; Luke 4:16–21 — Jesus reading the scroll in the synagogue and declaring it fulfilled in their hearing).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Moses took the blood and threw it on the people and said: Behold the blood of the covenant (<i>hinne dam habrit</i>) that YHWH has made with you in accordance with all these words.' This verse is directly quoted by Jesus at the Last Supper in all three Synoptics: 'This is my blood of the covenant' (Matt 26:28; Mark 14:24; Luke 22:20). Jesus's institution of the Eucharist uses the exact covenant-blood formula of Exod 24:8 to identify his death as the new covenant ratification event. Hebrews 9:18–21 develops the parallel explicitly: the first covenant was not inaugurated without blood.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Moses, Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and seventy elders of Israel went up and saw the God of Israel. The covenant ratification culminates in a theophany: the covenant leadership sees YHWH. This is the most extraordinary statement in Exodus — human beings see God and live. They saw the God of Israel — not a symbol, not an angel, but YHWH himself, in some form visible to human eyes. This corporate vision of God anticipates the NT promise: 'they will see his face' (Rev 22:4); 'we know that when he appears we shall be like him, because we shall see him as he is' (1 John 3:2).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Under his feet was something like a pavement of sapphire stone, like the very heaven for clearness.' The divine throne's footstool — the sapphire pavement beneath YHWH's feet. Ezekiel's throne-vision (Ezek 1:26; 10:1) uses the same sapphire imagery for the divine throne platform. John's throne-vision (Rev 4:6) describes 'a sea of glass, like crystal' before the throne. The visual consistency of these divine-throne descriptions across Scripture suggests a consistent heavenly reality partially glimpsed by different covenant witnesses across time.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'He did not lay his hand on the chief men of the people of Israel; they beheld God and ate and drank.' The covenant meal in the divine presence: the elders see God and eat together. This is the most striking theophany in the Hebrew Bible — a corporate meal in the direct divine presence, with no one struck dead. The NT fulfillment is the Lord's Supper: the covenant community eats and drinks in the presence of the risen Christ ('where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them,' Matt 18:20). The elders' meal before YHWH on Sinai is the OT form of the church's Eucharistic gathering.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH tells Moses to come up and receive the stone tablets with the law and commandments. The tablets are described as YHWH's own writing — he has written them for Israel's instruction. The written covenant given to Moses is the foundational document of Israel's covenant life. The NT contrast: 'not on tablets of stone but on tablets of human hearts' (2 Cor 3:3). The new covenant's writing medium — the human heart by the Spirit — is the fulfillment of what Jeremiah promised (31:33): the law internalized rather than externalized.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Moses arose with his assistant Joshua and went up the mountain of God. Joshua alone accompanies Moses partway up; the elders wait at a lower level. The ascending tiers of the mountain approach mirror the ascending holiness of the sanctuary: court, holy place, most holy place. Joshua's presence as assistant at this crucial moment is a foretaste: he will be the one who leads Israel into the land when Moses cannot. The servant who climbs furthest with the mediator inherits the mediator's mission.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Moses told the elders: 'Wait for us here until we return — Aaron and Hur are with you.' The delegation of authority in Moses's absence: Aaron and Hur as co-leaders during Moses's forty days. The disaster of the golden calf (ch. 32) will occur in Moses's absence — demonstrating that delegated authority (Aaron) without the mediator's personal presence is vulnerable to collapse. The NT pattern is different: Christ does not leave his community without his own presence ('I am with you always,' Matt 28:20) — the Spirit is the Paraclete, the one who stands alongside in the mediator's physical absence.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Moses went up and the cloud covered the mountain. The cloud of the divine presence — the same pillar of cloud that led Israel (Exod 13:21) — now settles on Sinai to cover Moses's ascent. The cloud marks the boundary between the divine and human realms: where the cloud descends, the divine presence is localized. The same cloud overshadows Jesus at the transfiguration (Matt 17:5) and at the ascension (Acts 1:9). The cloud is the consistent OT symbol of divine presence that the NT identifies as the medium of Christ's own glory-manifestation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The glory of YHWH (<i>kavod YHWH</i>) rested on Sinai for six days, and on the seventh YHWH called to Moses from the cloud. The six-day waiting period and seventh-day call mirrors the creation week — rest on the seventh day, then the new beginning. The pattern of six days of preparation and the seventh day of divine action recurs: Moses waits six days before being called into the divine presence. The seventh day is the day of encounter, of covenant, of new creation. The resurrection on the first/eighth day follows and fulfills this Sabbath-then-new-beginning pattern.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The appearance of the glory of YHWH was like a devouring fire (<i>esh okhelet*</i>) on the top of the mountain in the sight of the Israelites. The divine glory seen as fire: both consuming and illuminating, both terrifying and beautiful. This fire-glory appears in the burning bush (3:2), the pillar of fire (13:21), the Sinai theophany, the cloud filling the tabernacle (40:38), and ultimately in the Spirit's tongues of fire at Pentecost (Acts 2:3). The fire-glory of YHWH is the consistent manifestation of his presence, culminating in the Spirit's fire indwelling the community.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Moses entered the cloud and went up the mountain — Moses was on the mountain forty days and forty nights. The forty days and forty nights of Moses on Sinai sets the template for Israel's forty years in the wilderness and for Jesus's forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:1–2). The forty-unit period is the time of testing and formation: Moses received the law; Jesus recapitulated Israel's wilderness testing and succeeded where Israel failed. The number forty marks a period of transition between the old condition and the new covenant responsibility that follows.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus', existing)
    print('Exodus 22-24 mkt-christ written.')
    import pathlib
    out = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/commentary/mkt-christ/exodus.json').read_text())
    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/exodus.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in range(22, 25):
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys()) - set(out.get(ck, {}).keys())
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(out.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
